<subSubSection id="1BF0657C7134FFA4FF6F08160FD3FB25" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="535536F77134FFA4FF6F08160ABEFC05" blockId="3.[192,1440,628,1164]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
Identification of species within the obesus group has been complicated by erroneous species hypoth- eses and synonymies. Members of this species group can be readily separated from other Southeast Asian 
<taxonomicName id="94EA4D747134FFA4FE9108D10F45FD62" box="[272,378,691,715]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Nigidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="619EEAE57134FFA4FE9108D10F45FD62" box="[272,378,691,715]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Nigidius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by the presence of large, sub-oval lobes of the ocular canthus adjacent to the eyes (
<figureCitation id="CBD12A727134FFA4FE8408B60F75FD45" box="[261,330,724,748]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="3.[192,275,1877,1899]" captionTargetBox="[227,1426,1214,1817]" captionTargetId="graphics@3.[227,827,1214,1766]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. Species groups of Southeast Asian Nigidius species based on ocular canthus shape. 1a) Nigidius obesus group. 1b) cornutus group. 1c) distinctus group. 1d) laevicollis group." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3699465" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3699465/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). This is in contrast to other Southeast Asian groups that can be generalized as follows: b) the cornutus group, including 
<taxonomicName id="94EA4D747134FFA4FDB208960D03FCA5" authority="MacLeay" authorityName="MacLeay" authorityYear="1819" box="[563,828,756,780]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Nigidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cornutus">
<emphasis id="619EEAE57134FFA4FDB208960CFEFCA2" box="[563,705,756,779]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">N. cornutus</emphasis>
MacLeay
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="94EA4D747134FFA4FCC608960A71FCA5" authority="Okuda" authorityName="Okuda" authorityYear="2002" box="[839,1102,755,780]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Nigidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sabahensis">
<emphasis id="619EEAE57134FFA4FCC608960DCEFCA2" box="[839,1009,755,779]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">N. sabahensis</emphasis>
Okuda
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="94EA4D747134FFA4FB1108960B9FFCA2" authority="Van Roon" authorityName="Van Roon" authorityYear="1914" box="[1168,1440,755,779]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Nigidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oblongus">
<emphasis id="619EEAE57134FFA4FB1108960B1FFCA2" box="[1168,1312,755,779]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">N. oblongus</emphasis>
Van Roon
</taxonomicName>
with a shelf-like canthus that is truncate anteriorly; c) the distinctus group, including 
<taxonomicName id="94EA4D747134FFA4FA8009760F39FCE5" authority="Parry" authorityName="Parry" authorityYear="1873" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Nigidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="distinctus">
<emphasis id="619EEAE57134FFA4FA8009760B9FFC82" box="[1281,1440,787,811]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">N. distinctus</emphasis>
Parry
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="94EA4D747134FFA4FEC509560C2AFCE5" authority="Boileau" authorityName="Boileau" authorityYear="1905" box="[324,533,819,844]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Nigidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lewisi">
<emphasis id="619EEAE57134FFA4FEC509560F8FFCE2" box="[324,432,819,843]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">N. lewisi</emphasis>
Boileau
</taxonomicName>
with a deeply emarginate canthus; and d) the laevicollis group, including numerous species such as 
<taxonomicName id="94EA4D747134FFA4FD9109360D04FCC5" authority="Westwood" authorityName="Westwood" box="[528,827,851,876]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Nigidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevicollis">
<emphasis id="619EEAE57134FFA4FD9109360C8EFCC2" box="[528,689,851,875]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">N. laevicollis</emphasis>
Westwood
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="94EA4D747134FFA4FCCB09360A6EFCC5" authority="Boileau" authorityName="Boileau" authorityYear="1902" box="[842,1105,851,876]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Nigidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elongatus">
<emphasis id="619EEAE57134FFA4FCCB09360DD8FCC2" box="[842,999,851,875]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">N. elongatus</emphasis>
Boileau
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="94EA4D747134FFA4FB1B09360B9FFCC2" authority="Bates" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1866" box="[1178,1440,852,876]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Nigidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosanus">
<emphasis id="619EEAE57134FFA4FB1B09360B6FFCC5" box="[1178,1360,852,876]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">N. formosanus</emphasis>
Bates
</taxonomicName>
with a posteriorly expanding triangular canthus. In some species (such as 
<taxonomicName id="94EA4D747134FFA4FBC609160B47FC25" authority="Ritsema" authorityName="Ritsema" box="[1095,1400,883,908]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Nigidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kinabaluenis">
<emphasis id="619EEAE57134FFA4FBC609160B36FC22" box="[1095,1289,883,907]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">N. kinabaluenis</emphasis>
Ritsema
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="94EA4D747134FFA4FA0209160FF3FC05" authority="Ritsema" authorityName="Ritsema" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" genus="Nigidius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lichtensteinii">
<emphasis id="619EEAE57134FFA4FA0209160F61FC02" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">N. lichtensteinii</emphasis>
Ritsema
</taxonomicName>
) the canthus is weakly emarginate at the anterior third.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="535536F77134FFA4FF6C09D60FD3FB25" blockId="3.[192,1440,628,1164]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Within the obesus species group, species can be distinguished by the shape of the flagellum of the male genitalia, pronotal punctation, and the form of the anterolateral projection of the pronotum. Although useful for species diagnosis, the latter character is informative only for larger specimens because in all species the smaller individuals have a less well-developed projection. The form of the mandibles is conserved in these species, and partially sexually dimorphic. Large males can be sexed easily due to the broad lobe-like tooth near the base of the mandible. In females and small males, the tooth is much narrower and sub-acute.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
